		Depending on the system timezone, the ExportTest may fail. This is because the formatting of the SimpleDateFormat depends on the timezone used for "interpretation" of the millisecondsSince1970 value, as documented in the sample code of http://developer.android.com/reference/java/text/SimpleDateFormat.html Now we can fix the test by adding static {
    fieldNoteDateFormat.setTimeZone(TimeZone.getTimeZone("UTC"));
}
 and editing the expected output. But before doing that, I would like to know if someone knows how GC interprets the timezone of field note exports. Because if they use a timezone different to UTC, it might make more sense to use that one for the date format (but still leave the output format on Zulu time).

		Today a user told me that c:geo shows "0 m/h" as the speed. That's not miles per hour, but meters per hour. getSpeed() calls getDistanceFromKilometers() which calls scaleDistance():             if (distanceKilometers >= 1) {
                distance = distanceKilometers;
                units = "km";
            } else {
                distance = distanceKilometers * 1000;
                units = "m";
            } That means that the string will contain m/h as long as the speed is below 1 km/h. It looks like this behavior is intended.             TestSettings.setUseImperialUnits(false);
            assertSpeed("123 km/h", 122.782f);
            assertSpeed("123 km/h", 123.456f);
            assertSpeed("12.3 km/h", 12.3456f);
            assertSpeed("1.23 km/h", 1.23456f);
            assertSpeed("123 m/h", 0.123456f);
            TestSettings.setUseImperialUnits(true);
            assertSpeed("76.7 mph", 123.456f);
            assertSpeed("7.67 mph", 12.3456f);
            assertSpeed("0.77 mph", 1.23456f);
 I wonder if this high precision is really necessary. Before committing my changes I want to get feedback for the following results:             TestSettings.setUseImperialUnits(false);
            assertSpeed("123 km/h", 122.782f);
